EasyVisa Project

Context:

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired your firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent of the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

Function to create histogram-boxplot visualization

In [22]:
# function to create histogram-boxplot visualization

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Function to create labelled barplots

In [23]:
# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Leading Questions:

  1. Those with higher education may want to travel abroad for a well-paid job. Does education play a role in Visa certification?

  2. How does the visa status vary across different continents?

  3. Experienced professionals might look abroad for opportunities to improve their lifestyles and career development. Does work experience influence visa status?

  4. In the United States, employees are paid at different intervals. Which pay unit is most likely to be certified for a visa?

  5. The US government has established a prevailing wage to protect local talent and foreign workers. How does the visa status change with the prevailing wage?

Creating functions that will help us with further analysis

In [36]:
### function to plot distributions wrt target


def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0])

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
In [37]:
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

def stacked_barplot(data, case_status, region_of_employment):
    # Create a crosstab between the 'case_status' and 'region_of_employment' columns
    ct = pd.crosstab(data[case_status], data[region_of_employment], normalize='index') * 100  # Calculate percentages across the index axis

    # Plot the stacked bar plot
    ct.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.ylabel("Percentage")
    plt.title("Percentage of Visa Certifications Across Each Region")
    plt.show()

# Call the function with 'case_status' and 'region_of_employment'

Data Preparataion for model building

  • We want to predict which visa will be certified.
  • Before we proceed to build a model, we'll have to encode categorical features.
  • We'll split the data into train and test to be able to evaluate the model that we build on the train data.
  • When data (classification) exhibit a significant imbalance in the distribution of the target classes, it is good to use stratified sampling to ensure that relative class frequencies are approximately preserved in train and test sets.
  • This is done by setting the stratify parameter to target variable in the train_test_split function.
In [64]:
# Drop the 'case_status' column from the data and store the remaining columns in X
X = df.drop(['case_status'], axis=1)


# Assign the target variable 'case_status' to y
y = df["case_status"]

# Split the data into train and test sets in a 70:30 ratio
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=1, stratify=y)

Model Building

Model evaluation criterion

Model can make wrong predictions as:

  • Model predicts that the visa application will get certified but in reality, the visa application should get denied.

  • Model predicts that the visa application will not get certified but in reality, the visa application should get certified.

Which case is more important?

  • Both the cases are important as:

  • If a visa is certified when it had to be denied a wrong employee will get the job position while US citizens will miss the opportunity to work on that position.

  • If a visa is denied when it had to be certified the U.S. will lose a suitable human resource that can contribute to the economy.

How to reduce the losses?

  • F1 Score can be used a the metric for evaluation of the model, greater the F1 score higher are the chances of minimizing False Negatives and False Positives.

  • We will use balanced class weights so that model focuses equally on both classes.

We shall first create functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.

  • The model_performance_classification_sklearn function will be used to check the model performance of models.

The confusion_matrix_sklearn function will be used to plot the confusion matrix.

In [69]:
# Import necessary libraries
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

def model_performance_classification_sklearn(predictors, target, model):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    model: classifier
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # Compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # Compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # Compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # Compute F1-score

    print("Accuracy:", acc)
    print("Precision:", precision)
    print("Recall:", recall)
    print("F1-score:", f1)

    # Creating a dictionary of metrics for better readability
    perf_metrics = {"Accuracy": acc, "Precision": precision, "Recall": recall, "F1-score": f1}

    return perf_metrics
In [70]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(cm.shape[0], cm.shape[1])

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.show()

create a function to get future importance of the model classifiers

In [71]:
def get_feature_importance(estimator, X_train):
    if isinstance(estimator, DecisionTreeClassifier):
        return pd.DataFrame(estimator.feature_importances_, columns=["Imp"], index=X_train.columns).sort_values(by='Imp', ascending=False)
    else:
        if hasattr(estimator, 'feature_importances_'):
            feature_importances = estimator.feature_importances_
        else:
            feature_importances = None
        return feature_importances

def plot_feature_importance(ensemble_method, X_train, y_train):
    ensemble_methods = [DecisionTreeClassifier, BaggingClassifier, RandomForestClassifier, AdaBoostClassifier, GradientBoostingClassifier, XGBClassifier, StackingClassifier]
    
    if type(ensemble_method) in ensemble_methods:
        ensemble_method.fit(X_train, y_train)

        feature_importance_dict = {}

        if isinstance(ensemble_method, StackingClassifier):
            for name, est in ensemble_method.named_estimators_.items():
                feature_importances = get_feature_importance(est, X_train)
                if feature_importances is not None:
                    for i, imp in enumerate(feature_importances):
                        if X_train.columns[i] in feature_importance_dict:
                            feature_importance_dict[X_train.columns[i]] += imp
                        else:
                            feature_importance_dict[X_train.columns[i]] = imp
        else:
            feature_importances = get_feature_importance(ensemble_method, X_train)
            if feature_importances is not None:
                for i, imp in enumerate(feature_importances):
                    if X_train.columns[i] in feature_importance_dict:
                        feature_importance_dict[X_train.columns[i]] += imp
                    else:
                        feature_importance_dict[X_train.columns[i]] = imp

        total = sum(feature_importance_dict.values())
        normalized_feature_imp = {k: v / total for k, v in feature_importance_dict.items()}

        feature_importance_df = pd.DataFrame(list(normalized_feature_imp.items()), columns=['Feature', 'Importance'])
        feature_importance_df = feature_importance_df.sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)

        if isinstance(ensemble_method, (DecisionTreeClassifier, BaggingClassifier, RandomForestClassifier)):
            importances_df = pd.DataFrame(ensemble_method.feature_importances_.reshape(-1, 1), columns=["Imp"], index=X_train.columns[:len(ensemble_method.feature_importances_)])

        print(importances_df)

        plt.figure(figsize=(12,12))
        plt.barh(range(len(feature_importance_df)), feature_importance_df['Importance'], color='violet', align='center')
        plt.yticks(range(len(feature_importance_df)), feature_importance_df['Feature'])
        plt.xlabel('Relative Importance')
        plt.title(f'Feature Importances for {type(ensemble_method).__name__}')
        plt.show()
    else:
        print("Ensemble method not supported for feature importance analysis.")

Building Esemble Models

Building the model

  • We are going to build 3 ensemble models here - AdaBoost Classifier, Gradient Boosting Classifier and XGBoost Classifier.

  • First, let's build these models with default parameters and then use hyperparameter tuning to optimize the model performance.

  • We will calculate all three metrics - Accuracy, Precision and Recall but the metric of interest here is recall.

  • Recall - It gives the ratio of True positives to Actual positives, so high Recall implies low false negatives, i.e. low chances of predicting an employee with certified visa status as employee with denied visa status.

create functions to calculate different metrics and plot the confusion matrix.

In [119]:
## Function to create confusion matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(model,y_actual,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth  
    
    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(X_test)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
In [120]:
# Function to calculate evaluation metrics
def calculate_metrics(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):
    # Fit the model
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    # Make predictions
    y_pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    y_pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Calculate evaluation metrics
    train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    test_acc = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    train_recall = recall_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    test_recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    train_precision = precision_score(y_train, y_pred_train)
    test_precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred_test)
    train_f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_train, pred_train)
    test_f1 = metrics.f1_score(y_test, pred_test)
    
    return train_acc, test_acc, train_recall, test_recall, train_precision, test_precision

# Function to plot confusion matrix
def plot_confusion_matrix(model, X_test, y_test, model_name):
    # Make predictions
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    # Plot confusion matrix
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', ax=ax)
    ax.set_xlabel('Predicted labels')
    ax.set_ylabel('True labels')
    ax.set_title(f'Confusion Matrix - {model_name}')
    plt.show()

Will tuning the hyperparameters improve the model performance?¶

Hperparameter Tuning- AdaBoost Classifier

  • An AdaBoost classifier is a meta-estimator that begins by fitting a classifier on the original dataset and then fits additional copies of the classifier on the same dataset but where the weights of incorrectly classified instances are adjusted such that subsequent classifiers focus more on difficult cases.

  • Some important hyperparamters are:

    • base_estimator: The base estimator from which the boosted ensemble is built.
    • By default the base estimator is a decision tree with max_dept=1.
    • n_estimators: The maximum number of estimators at which boosting is terminatedDefault value is 50.

learning_rate: Learning rate shrinks the contribution of each classifier by learning_rate. There is a trade-off between learning_rate a d n_estimarto

In [136]:
# Choose the type of classifier. 
abc_tuned = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
## add from article
parameters = {
    "n_estimators": np.arange(50,110,25),
    "learning_rate": [0.01,0.1,0.05],
    "base_estimator": [
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, random_state=1),
        DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, random_state=1),
    ],
}
# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(abc_tuned, parameters, scoring=acc_scorer,cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
abc_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
abc_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

XGBoost Classifier

XGBoost has many hyper parameters which can be tuned to increase the model performance. You can read about them in the xgboost documentation here. Some of the important parameters are:

  • scale_pos_weight:Control the balance of positive and negative weights, useful for unbalanced classes. It has range from 0 to ∞.

subsample: Corresponds to the fraction of observations (the rows) to subsample at each step. By default it is set to 1 meaning that we use all row

  • .

colsample_bytree: Corresponds to the fraction of features (the columns) to u

  • e.

colsample_bylevel: The subsample ratio of columns for each level. Columns are subsampled from the set of columns chosen for the current t

  • ee.

colsample_bynode: The subsample ratio of columns for each node (split). Columns are subsampled from the set of columns chosen for the current l

  • mel.

max_depth: is the maximum number of nodes allowed from the root to the farthest leaf of a

  • tree.

learning_rate/eta: Makes the model more robust by shrinking the weights on eac

  • step.

gamma: A node is split only when the resulting split gives a positive reduction in the loss function. Gamma specifies the minimum loss reduction required to make a split.a split.

from tabulate import tabulate

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

model_names = [
    "Decision Tree", "Tuned Decision Tree", "Bagging", "Bagging with Weighted Samples",
    "Tuned Bagging", "Random Forest", "Random Forest with Weighted Samples", "Tuned Random Forest",
    "AdaBoost", "Tuned AdaBoost", "Gradient Boosting", "Initial Gradient Boosting", 
    "Tuned Gradient Boosting", "XGBoost", "Tuned XGBoost", "Stacking Estimator"
]

models = [
    dtree, dtree_tuned, bagging, bagging_wt, bagging_tuned, rf, rf_wt, rf_tuned, abc, abc_tuned, gbc, 
    gbc_init, gbc_tuned, xgb, xgb_tuned, stacking_estimator
]

metrics_table_train = []
metrics_table_test = []

for name, model in zip(model_names, models):
    pred_train = model.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = model.predict(X_test)
    
    accuracy_train = accuracy_score(y_train, pred_train)
    precision_train = precision_score(y_train, pred_train)
    recall_train = recall_score(y_train, pred_train)
    f1_train = f1_score(y_train, pred_train)
    
    accuracy_test = accuracy_score(y_test, pred_test)
    precision_test = precision_score(y_test, pred_test)
    recall_test = recall_score(y_test, pred_test)
    f1_test = f1_score(y_test, pred_test)
    
    metrics_table_train.append([name, accuracy_train, precision_train, recall_train, f1_train])
    metrics_table_test.append([name, accuracy_test, precision_test, recall_test, f1_test])

headers = ["Model", "Accuracy", "Precision", "Recall", "F1-Score"]

print("Training Set Performance:")
print(tabulate(metrics_table_train, headers=headers, tablefmt="grid"))
print("\n")
print("Testing Set Performance:")
print(tabulate(metrics_table_test, headers=headers, tablefmt="grid"))

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

**Actionable Insights** * The factors that ultimately decide visa status of an employee in the decreasing order of their importance are Education level or qualification of an employee(25.38% relative importance), unit of wages( 18.08% relative importance), job esperience(12.88% relative importance), prevailing wage(8.64%), number of employees and age of company ( both have ~3% relative importance), while region of employment and continent have ~2% relative importance each. * The wage level associated with the job is an influential factor in the visa approval process. Higher wages may indicate higher-skilled positions with potentially better chances of approval. * Prevailing wage holds a significant influence on visa approval decisions, accounting for 8.64% relative importance in the model. This factor signifies the importance of offering competitive wages in alignment with industry standards for visa approval. * The number of employees within the company plays a notable role in the visa approval process, accounting for about 3% relative importance. This factor may reflect the organization's stability, growth potential, and its capacity to support additional employment. * Highlight the company's growth trajectory and its ability to create employment opportunities when submitting visa applications. Emphasize the positive impact of hiring additional employees on the local economy and workforce. * The age of the company is a contributing factor with around 3% relative importance in visa approval decisions. The longevity and establishment of the company may signal reliability, experience, and commitment to long-term operations. * Other factors like full time position, and requires job training have less than 1% relative importance each. **Recommendation:** * Data Transparency and Documentation:Ensure that all visa applications include clear and comprehensive documentation related to the education level and qualifications of the employees. Highlight the relevance of their educational background to the job roles they are applying for. * Focus on Competitive Compensation:Emphasize the importance of competitive wages aligned with industry standards to enhance the chances of visa approval. Providing attractive remuneration packages can support visa applications for skilled workers. * Training and Skill Development Programs:While job training may have a lower relative importance in the final model, investing in training and skill development programs for employees can enhance their overall competency and performance. Strengthening employees' skills can have a positive impact on visa approval and job success. * Continuous Monitoring and Adjustment:Regularly monitor and analyze the factors influencing visa approval to adapt strategies accordingly. Stay informed about regulatory changes, visa requirements, and market trends to optimize the visa application process. * Leverage Insights for Strategic Decision-making:Utilize the actionable insights derived from the model's important features to inform strategic decision-making related to visa approvals. Tailoring visa applications based on the highlighted factors can increase the likelihood of successful approvals. * While full-time positions may not heavily impact visa approval, ensure that job roles and positions align with regulatory requirements and are clearly articulated within visa applications. Highlight the stability and commitment of full-time roles for sustainable employment. * Consider conducting a temporal analysis to assess how visa approval trends have evolved over time. Analyze historical data to identify patterns, changes in approval criteria, and regulatory updates that may impact visa application outcomes. * Implement a feedback loop mechanism to gather insights from rejected visa applications and incorporate the feedback into the model training process. Utilize rejected application data to identify common reasons for denial and refine the model accorfingly. * Conduct a more detailed examination of the relative importance of each feature in the model to identify additional key determinants of visa approval. This analysis can provide deeper insights into the impact of various factors on the decision-making process. * The final model can further be fine tuned. Adjusting hyperparameters can lead to improved model robustness and efficiecy. * By incorporating these actionable insights and recommendations, organizations can improve their visa approval rates, enhance employee retention, and align with regulations effectively when facilitating international workfore .
